Two bugs to fix in the diff viewer:

## Bug 1 — Syntax highlighting not working

tree-sitter.wasm core file needs to be loaded from the correct path.
Check where TreeSitterParser initialises web-tree-sitter and ensure it
loads from public/tree-sitter/tree-sitter.wasm.

Also check vite.config.ts — the public/ directory contents must be
served correctly in both dev and production Electron builds. The wasm
files must be accessible at runtime.

If TreeSitterParser is catching parse errors silently and falling back
to plain text, add a console.warn so we can see what is failing.

## Bug 2 — Whole line highlighted instead of changed tokens

Currently when a line is modified (not added or removed entirely) the
whole line gets a red or green background. This is wrong.

Example:
  left:  import { join } from "path";
  right: import { join, resolve } from "path";

Expected behaviour:
  - The line background should be a muted red/green (not full intensity)
  - Only the changed token — ", resolve" — should have a full intensity
    highlight within the line

This is called word-level diff or intra-line diff.

Implementation:
  In JsDiffEngine, for lines that are modified (appear as one removed +
  one added in the same hunk), compute a character-level diff using
  Diff.diffChars() from the diff package.

  Return an additional field on modified lines:
    charDiff?: { left: CharRange[]; right: CharRange[] }
  where CharRange is:
    { start: number; end: number; type: 'added' | 'removed' | 'unchanged' }

  In DiffViewer, when rendering a modified line:
  - Apply a muted background to the whole line (--color-diff-added-muted
    and --color-diff-removed-muted, define these as more transparent
    versions of the existing diff colours)
  - Render the line content as spans, applying full intensity highlight
    only to the changed character ranges

  A line is considered "modified" (not fully added/removed) when a
  removed line and an added line appear as a pair within the same hunk
  and their content similarity is above 30% (use Diff.diffChars length
  ratio to determine similarity).

